    clinicalRelevance: "Chronic phase: leukocytosis with left shift (all stages of myeloid maturation visible), basophilia, eosinophilia, thrombocytosis, splenomegaly. Low LAP (leukocyte alkaline phosphatase) score distinguishes CML from leukemoid reaction (high LAP). Blast crisis: transformation to acute leukemia (myeloid 60%, lymphoid 30%).",
    signsSymptoms: "Fatigue, weight loss, night sweats, early satiety (splenomegaly—often massive), abdominal pain. WBC often >100 ×10⁹/L at diagnosis.",
    assessment: "CBC: marked leukocytosis (50,000-500,000/μL), left shift with all myeloid stages, basophilia (>2%), eosinophilia, thrombocytosis. LAP score: LOW (vs HIGH in leukemoid reaction, infection, PV). Peripheral smear: neutrophilic left shift with myelocytes, metamyelocytes, bands, and mature neutrophils; basophilia. Cytogenetics: t(9;22) Philadelphia chromosome. Molecular: BCR-ABL1 by RT-PCR (most sensitive for monitoring).",
